Short SummaryHello from the Inclusive Practices team!The NGO Inclusive Practices (IP) is a team of psychologists, teachers and social workers that for more than 20 years has been developing and implementing social inclusion programs in post-Soviet countries. Team’s considerable conceptual and practical experience became the foundation for development of the NGO Inclusive Practices that was registered in January 2018 in Ureki, Georgia.IP is a member and partner of the International Association for Community Development – IACD Global – the only global multidisciplinary professional community development network. The IACD committed to promote participative democracy, sustainable development, rights, economic opportunity, equality and social justice, through the organization, education and empowerment of people within their communities. The IACD is accredited by the UN and has members all around the world.IP is a member of the Inclusion International - the international network of people with intellectual disabilities and their families that advocates human rights and rights of persons with intellectual disabilities globally. For more than 50 years, the Inclusion International has promoted human rights and is now represented by more than 200 member federations in 115 countries on five continents including Near East and North Africa, Europe, Africa, Americas and Asia-Pacific.For more than 3 years, we invest our time, work, money and other resources in the development of the strongest inclusive community. At our own expense with no additional funding we held inclusive festivals, conferences, competitions, etc., that included thousands of participants.Here’s the info about our festivals:1. Our First International Inclusive Practices Festival "PUSHING THE LIMITS - 2018". These were exciting days! Amazing people, useful projects, unique performances:

 
2. Our International Inclusive Practices Festivals "PUSHING THE LIMITS - 2019" is a great site for internship for future psychologists, teachers, social workers, coaches and other practitioners working in inclusion.What We Need &amp; What You GetDuring the global pandemic, our Virtual Platform gained unprecedented success and in 2,5 months 5000 people became its active audience. IP Virtual Platform includes 35 sections, people from 17 countries, and hundreds of persons with disabilities that present their projects to the world. The interest in the platform is so high that we haven’t got enough resources to accommodate and support all those who want to join. Today you can help a maximum number of persons with disabilities from Europe and USA to join our platform and learn to use all the benefits it offers.Inclusive Practices Virtual Platform (IPVP) is a virtual open space that brings together more than 500 inclusive initiatives in inclusive arts, sports, education and learning, volunteering, tourism, etc. At the heart of this project is an international community of social inclusion practitioners from Armenia, Belarus, Bulgaria, the UK, Germany, Georgia, Italy, Kazakhstan, Kenia, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, the Netherlands, Portugal, Russia, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan and Ukraine. Every day, in livestream format, the IPVP presents discussions on relevant issues of inclusive practices, Zoom meetings, webinars, presentations, online competitions and events, documentaries and many more.How can you help?We are holding the Inclusive Practices without Limits competition that allows socially active persons with disabilities to compete for a main prize – a certificate for an internship program on the base of the IPVP. The certificates for the first group of interns were paid for by the IP, but there are more people who are interested in the internship, our program attracts more and more active people, and while the IP has human capital and technical capacity, we need for the certificates to be paid for. All the funds will be used to remunerate coaches’ work and pay for the utilities, technical support and Internet promotion.That’s why we ask for your help. One certificate costs 300 USD. One certificate is one month of intensive study. One certificate is a chance for one person with a disability to become successful and to find their purpose and place on the international Inclusive Practices Platform.With your help we can make more persons with disabilities successful. We invite you to become a participant of the development of an inclusive community without limits.Why do you need it?
In this project you can become a full-fledged participant in the development of an inclusive community without limits. By helping our project, wherever you live, you’ll become a person of the World:
You’ll be invited to take part in a discussion on the topic of inclusive community development;
You’ll be a guest when the interns will present the outcomes of their studies;
You’ll receive a thanks letter from the international Inclusive Practices Team;
You’ll receive a newsletter that will allow you to follow the interns progress;
We’ll talk about you in our social media:
You can become an official donor of one of the sections on the Inclusive Practices Virtual Platform.
 We don’t look just for sponsors, we develop an active community of those who care and are ready to be a part of the development of an inclusive community. We don’t just ask for your money, we’d like to engage strong and active persons who want to contribute to the good cause. Do not donate, if you don’t share our views and you are not enthusiastic about it.The ImpactPlease, learn more about the successful projects that we had accomplished:The IP CompetitionThe first International Competition “The Best Inclusive Practices 2018” encompassed various directions of social inclusion such as art therapy, inclusive sports, family inclusion, creative inclusive collectives, authorial projects. The purpose of the competition was information support and promotion of successful inclusive practices. The first prise in the competition was production of the full-time documentary about the winning project.The winner of the first International Competition “The Best Inclusive Practices 2018” was the project “Future teacher – A child with special needs – Parents: the points of contact” from Chernivtsi, Ukraine.The next competition was focused not only on successful, well established inclusive projects, but also on new, fledgling ideas and initiatives in social inclusion. That’s why this competition we named “Inclusive Practices of the Future: Ideas, Research, Innovations”.In 2019, the first prize was shared between two winners:
Elena Maslova from Minsk, Belarus, and her project “Inclusive practice in the organization of the choir collective as a system of development of communicative competence in students” and
Zulfia Troska from Moscow, Russia, with her project “The school of inclusive volunteering”.
Social inclusion is actively developing; new directions continuously emerge as well as new horizons open. One of the trends is inclusive community development.Our third International Inclusive Practices competition “Inclusive Community Leader 2020” is dedicated to this topic. In line with the theme of the competition, the winner received a ticket to the World Community Development Conference 2021 (WCDC2021).Yulia Zherlitsina from Kyiv, Ukraine, a director of the Public Organization “The Hive of Ideas” and the author of the project “A Native Lullaby” received an opportunity to present her experience in community development during the WCDC2021.We also held three very engaging marathons and we’d like to tell about one of them:The II Inclusive Practices Marathon ‘Inclusive Community: Here and Now’ (IP-Marathon) took place on November 9-15 2020. The purpose of the IP-Marathon is to develop a remote discussion platform for exchange of experience in the area of inclusive initiatives as well as to provide information support for inclusive community development practitioners.817 participants from 9 countries (Armenia, Belarus, the UK, Georgia, Kazakhstan, the Netherlands, Russia, Uzbekistan and Ukraine) took part in the IP-Marathon. Among the participants were practitioners, parents raising children with developmental challenges, inclusive community organizers and leaders, university professors and students, inclusive programs developers, heads of organizations and educational institutions.The IP-Marathon program included: presentations on successful inclusive practices experiences; authors’ Zoom-seminars; online discussions on pressing issues in social inclusion; training sessions on inclusive community model visualization; photo exhibition ‘Pushing the Limits – 2020’; inclusive flash mobs by the Children’s Inclusive Community; brainstorms for practitioners in the inclusion area; inclusive online NON!SCHOOL; the finale of the international inclusive competition for school and university students ‘Points of Contact’; premiere of the video project ‘Inclusive Culture in Society – the Magic of Touch and Glance’; the main stages of the international competition ‘Leader of inclusive community – 2020’.IP-Marathon became a platform for 77 speakers who gave speeches on various aspects of social inclusion: art therapy; inclusive education; inclusive theater; inclusive dances; inclusive creative teams; inclusive sports; inclusive tourism; alternative forms of inclusive creativity; inclusive communities/social associations; inclusive events; social inclusive initiatives; inclusive laboratories; digital and Internet technologies for inclusion.The overall broadcasting time of the IP-Marathon (from Monday to Sunday) was 57 hours. The main inclusive events were live streamed on Inclusive Practices’ Facebook page and YouTube channel. During the week more than 30 000 viewers watched the recordings of these live streams.Risks &amp; ChallengesThe possibly most damaging situation – a global Covid-19 pandemic, has already happened. We are proud to say that we were not only able to survive the hard times, but we also took a step forward. We were able to make a modern world more ACCESSIBLE to the persons with disabilities. This is the fact. Now it’s only a question how many people will be able to overcome the obstacles and enter an active social space.The only risk there is if the Internet would be down all over the world… but? We believe, Elon Musk promised not to let this happen.Other Ways You Can HelpIf you don’t have the means to help us, we will help you and it’s fine. If you personally know a person or persons with disabilities or volunteers, share our contacts with them and they will be able to join our inclusive community. We speak multiple languages and will be happy to lend our support to any person from any corner of the world.Our YouTube channel https://www.youtube.com/c/INCLUSIVEPRACTICESOur Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/inclusivepracticesOur Instagram https://www.instagram.com/inclusive_practices/Our Telegram Channel https://t.me/inclusivepractices  Используйте # ipVirtualPlatform для навигации в социальных сетяхДля получения дополнительных вопросов и информации напишите нам по адресу info@inclusivepractices.net+995579 215590 (WhatsApp, Viber, Telegram)
